    <text>
        <body><div type="bibliography">
                
                <p><bibl>Morelli in<ptr target="#SECir"/>, <citedRange>299</citedRange> (no image)</bibl>;
                    <bibl><ptr target="#IGCyr"/> <citedRange>106630</citedRange></bibl>.</p>    
              </div><div type="edition" xml:lang="grc" xml:space="preserve">
                
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1"/><persName type="attested" key="http://clas-lgpn2.classics.ox.ac.uk/cgi-bin/lgpn_search.cgi?id=V1-61397"><name nymRef="#Κλευγένης">Κλευγένης</name> 
                    <lb n="2"/><persName type="attested" key="http://clas-lgpn2.classics.ox.ac.uk/cgi-bin/lgpn_search.cgi?id=V1-61246"><name nymRef="#Ἐπίνικος" type="patronymic">Ἐπινίκου</name></persName></persName>
                </ab></div><div type="apparatus" xml:space="preserve">
            
                <p/>
               </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="fr">
            <p>Kleugénès fils d'Epinikos.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="en">
            <p>Kleugenes son of Epinikos.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="it">
            <p>Kleugenes figlio di Epinikos.</p>
         </div><div type="commentary">
                
                <p>This inscription was published by Morelli without photograph.</p> 
                <p>The same date in second century BC was given in <bibl><ptr target="#fraser-matthews1987"/></bibl>, obviously from Reynolds' advice
                and in private communication by Laronde to Dobias-Lalou, who could unfortunately not trace the stone in the Tolmeita Museum.</p>
                <p/>
            </div></body>
